  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT334-kilavi">varaiviṭai “āṟṟakiṟṟiyō” eṉṟa tōḻikkuk kiḻatti colliyatu. </p>


        <p xml:lang="en">Uttered by HER to the confidante, who had said “don't
          you have the strength [to await] the time of marriage?” </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT334">
          <l> ciṟuveṇ kākkaic cevvāyp peruntō</l>
          <l> ṭeṟitirait tivalai yīrmpuṟa naṉaippap</l>
          <l> paṉipulan tuṟaiyum palpūṅ kāṉal</l>
          <l> virinīrc cērppa ṉīppi ṉorunam</l>
          <l> miṉṉuyi rallatu piṟitoṉ</l>
          <l> ṟevaṉō tōḻi nāmiḻap patuvē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>If he leaves [us], the man from the coast of the broad water</l>
          <l rend="indent">with many-flowered seashore groves,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">where the red-mouthed big flock of little white crows <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> ciṟu veḷ kākkai </term>, in this formulaic expression, probably refers rather to seagulls than to crows (see, however, note on KT 246.1). </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent2">are continuously  <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> pulantu uṟaiyum </term> can be taken as an auxiliary construction. Or else: "sulks with the dew [and yet] remains". </note>  vexed by the dew <note place="foot"> To call the wetness, which distresses the birds, paṉi probably implies a play with the different notions of the word, which means predominantly "dew", then "the season of dew" and, because this is the cold season, also "coldness", and moreover it denotes also the illness associated with that season, a kind of shivering fever. </note> ,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">since it wets [their] backs [already] moist from the drops thrown</l>
          <l rend="indent8">by the waves</l>
          <l>– what else, friend, is it that we can lose</l>
          <l>than our one sweet life?</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
